\b0\fs26 	 
\i\fs22 Flerovium
\i0  (Fl) is a temporary {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IUPAC"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 IUPAC}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Systematic_element_name"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 systematic element name}}. The element is often referred to as 
\b element 114
\b0 , for its atomic number.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa100
\cf0 According to IUPAC recommendations, the discoverer(s) of a new element has the right to suggest a name.
\fs18 \cf2 [9]
\fs22 \cf0  The discovery of Flerovium was recognized by JWG of IUPAC on 1 June 2011, along with that of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ununhexium"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 ununhexium}}.
\fs18 \cf2 [8]
\fs22 \cf0  According to the vice-director of JINR,
\fs18 \cf2 [1]
\fs22 \cf0  the Dubna team would like to name element 114 
\i flerovium
\i0 ,
\fs18 \cf2 [10]
\fs22 \cf0  after Soviet physicist {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgy_Flyorov"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Georgy Flyorov}} (also spelled Flerov).
