\b\fs22 Flerovium
\b0  is the temporary name of a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioactivity"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 radioactive}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_element"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 chemical element}} with the temporary symbol 
\b Fl
\b0  and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_number"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 atomic number}} 114. There is no proposed name yet, although 
\i flerovium
\i0  (after Soviet physicist {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgy_Flyorov"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Georgy Flyorov}}, the founder of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_Institute_for_Nuclear_Research"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Joint Institute for Nuclear Research}} in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dubna"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Dubna}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russia"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Russia}}, where the element was discovered) has been discussed in the media.
\fs18 \cf2 [1]
\fs22 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa100
\cf0 About 80 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioactive_decay"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 decays}} of atoms of Flerovium have been observed to date, 50 directly and 30 from the decay of the heavier elements {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ununhexium"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 ununhexium}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ununoctium"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 ununoctium}}. All decays have been assigned to the five neighbouring {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isotope"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 isotopes}} with mass numbers 285\'96289. The longest-lived isotope currently known is 
\fs18 \super 289
\fs22 \nosupersub Fl with a half-life of ~2.6 s, although there is evidence for a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_isomer"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 nuclear isomer}}, 
\fs18 \super 289b
\fs22 \nosupersub Fl, with a half-life of ~66 s, that would be one of the longest-lived nuclei in the superheavy element region.\
Chemical studies performed in 2007 strongly indicate that Flerovium possesses non-{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mendeleev%27s_predicted_elements"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 eka-lead}} properties and appears to behave as the first superheavy element that portrays {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noble_gas"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 noble-gas}}-like properties due to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relativistic_quantum_chemistry"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 relativistic effects}}.
\fs18 \cf2 [2]
