\fs18 \super 289
\fs22 \nosupersub 114. This observation was subsequently published in January 1999.
\fs18 \cf2 [3]
\fs22 \cf0  However, the decay chain observed has not been repeated and the exact identity of this activity is unknown, although it is possible that it is due to a meta-stable isomer, namely 
\fs18 \super 289m
\fs22 \nosupersub Fl.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa100
\cf0 In March 1999, the same team replaced the 
\fs18 \super 244
\fs22 \nosupersub Pu target with a 
\fs18 \super 242
\fs22 \nosupersub Pu one in order to produce other isotopes. This time two atoms of Flerovium were produced, decaying by 10.29 MeV alpha-emission with a half-life of 5.5 s. They were assigned as 
\fs18 \super 287
\fs22 \nosupersub Fl.
\fs18 \cf2 [4]
\fs22 \cf0  Once again, this activity has not been seen again and it is unclear what nucleus was produced. It is possible that it was a meta-stable isomer, namely 
\fs18 \super 287m
\fs22 \nosupersub Fl.\
The now-confirmed discovery of Flerovium was made in June 1999 when the Dubna team repeated the 
\fs18 \super 244
\fs22 \nosupersub Pu reaction. This time, two atoms of element 114 were produced decaying by emission of 9.82\'a0MeV alpha particles with a half-life of 2.6\'a0s.
\fs18 \cf2 [5]
\fs22 \cf0 \
This activity was initially assigned to 
\fs18 \super 288
\fs22 \nosupersub Fl in error, due to the confusion regarding the above observations. Further work in Dec 2002 has allowed a positive reassignment to 
\fs18 \super 289
\fs22 \nosupersub 114.
